    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm having some trouble with my sourdough. the starter is super inconsistent lately. can u explain the actual science of how the wild yeast and lactobacilli actually interact with temperature and hydration to produce the CO2? like what's happening at a microscopic level to make it rise?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The inconsistent sourdough starter is a common issue, and understanding the microscopic interactions between wild yeast and lactobacilli is key to resolving it. The process of fermentation is a complex interplay of microbial interactions, temperature, and hydration. At a microscopic level, the wild yeast (typically Saccharomyces cerevisiae) and lactobacilli (such as Lactobacillus sanfranciscensis) work together to break down sugars and produce CO2.\n\nThe wild yeast ferments sugars, producing ethanol and CO2 as byproducts. However, the lactobacilli, which are more tolerant of acidic environments, take over the fermentation process once the wild yeast has exhausted the available sugars. This process is known as \"lactic acid fermentation.\" The lactobacilli convert the remaining sugars into lactic acid, which lowers the pH and creates an acidic environment that inhibits the growth of other microorganisms.\n\nTemperature plays a crucial role in this process. Wild yeast thrives in temperatures between 75°F and 85°F (24°C and 30°C), while lactobacilli prefer temperatures between 50°F and 60°F (10°C and 15°C). When the temperature is too high, the wild",
