      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interaction between the amylase enzymes and the microbes in the sourdough starter is a fascinating process. The amylase enzymes, which break down starches into simpler sugars, are produced by both the wild yeast and the lactobacilli.\n\nThe wild yeast produces amylase enzymes that are more efficient at breaking down complex starches, such as those found in wheat flour. These enzymes work optimally at temperatures between 75°F and 85°F (24°C and 30°C), which is why the wild yeast is more active at warmer temperatures.\n\nThe lactobacilli, on the other hand, produce amylase enzymes that are more efficient at breaking down simpler sugars, such as maltose and dextrins. These enzymes work optimally at temperatures between 50°F and 60°F (10°C and 15°C), which is why the lactobacilli are more active at cooler temperatures.\n\nWhen the wild yeast and lactobacilli are present together in the sourdough starter, they work in concert to break down the starches in the flour. The wild yeast produces amylase enzymes that break down the complex starches, while the lactobacilli produce amylase enzymes that break down",
